.TH taskd 1 2012-07-03 "${PACKAGE_STRING}" "User Manuals"

.SH NAME
taskd \- Task Server

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B taskd <command> [options] [<args>]
.br
.B taskd --version

.SH DESCRIPTION
Taskd is ...

.SH COMMANDS
Taskd supports several fixed commands, which perform high level functionality,
which can be extended via plugins to add functionality.

The commands are:

.TP
.B taskd init [--nohooks] [OPTIONS]
Performs a one-time initialization of the project.  Detects the SCM system in
use, which includes 'none'.  Creates local data structures.

.TP
.B taskd help <command> [OPTIONS]

.TP
.B taskd config [<name> [<value>]]

.TP
.B taskd status [OPTIONS]

.TP
.B taskd server [OPTIONS]
Starts the daemon.

.SH COMMON OPTIONS
Most commands support the following options:

.TP
.B --NAME=VALUE
Temporary configuration override.

.TP
.B --quiet
Suppresses verbose output.

.SH CONFIGURATION
Configuration files can be found ...

Note that any configuration variable may be overridden on the command line using
this syntax:

  $ taskd build --NAME=VALUE

In all commands but one, this will _temporarily_ override the value, but with
the 'init' command, which creates a config file, overrides are made permanent.

